Let's now calculate the present value of the investment at the initial rate of 10%.


$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value of an Annuity} &=\$8,500\times\dfrac{1-\dfrac{1}{\left(1+0.10\right)^{11}}}{0.10}
\\[10pt]
&=\$8,500\times\dfrac{0.6496}{0.10}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$55,208.02}
\end{aligned}$$

**As can be seen in our calculation, the present value of the investment at initial rate of 10% is $55,208.02.**

Next, let's now determine the effect in our investment if the interest rate suddenly drop to 5%.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value of an Annuity} &=\$8,500\times\dfrac{1-\dfrac{1}{\left(1+0.05\right)^{11}}}{0.05}
\\[10pt]
&=\$8,500\times\dfrac{0.4153}{0.05}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$70,604.52}
\end{aligned}$$

**Therefore, if the rate suddenly drops to 5% the value of our investment will increase to $70,604.52.**

Last, let's determine the effect in our investment if the interest rate increase to 15%.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Present Value of an Annuity} &=\$8,500\times\dfrac{1-\dfrac{1}{\left(1+0.05\right)^{11}}}{0.05}
\\[10pt]
&=\$8,500\times\dfrac{0.7851}{0.05}
\\[10pt]
&= \boxed{\bf\$44,486.55}
\end{aligned}$$

**Hence, if the interest rate increases to 15% the value of our investment will decrease to $44,486.55.**
